            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1969-02-05T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1969-02-05T00:00:00-05:00" n="63"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d63">
                <head>63. Memorandum From the President’s Assistant for National Security Affairs
                        (<persName corresp="#p_KHA1" type="from">Kissinger</persName>) to President
                        <persName corresp="#p_NRM1" type="to">Nixon</persName>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d63fn1">Source: National Archives, Nixon
                        Presidential Materials, <gloss target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> Files, <gloss
                            target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> Institutional Files (H-Files), Box H–136,
                            <gloss target="#t_NSSM1">NSSM</gloss> 20. Secret. <persName
                            corresp="#p_NRM1">Nixon</persName> initialed his approval of both of
                            <persName corresp="#p_KHA1">Kissinger</persName>’s
                        recommendations.</note>
                    <note n="2" type="summary" xml:id="d63fn2">
                        <persName corresp="#p_KHA1">Kissinger</persName> recommended holding an
                            <gloss target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> meeting to discuss the issues on the
                        agenda for the upcoming Eighteen-Nation Disarmament Conference (<gloss
                            target="#t_ENDC1">ENDC</gloss>) meeting in Geneva. In addition to this
                        conference, he also recommended that an ad hoc study group be established to
                        prepare a paper on the issues likely to be discussed, including the
                        comprehensive test ban, ending production of fissionable material, and
                        seabed arms control.</note>
                </head>
                <dateline>
                    <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1969-02-05"
                        >February 5, 1969</date>
                </dateline>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT:</head>
                    <item>U.S. Position for <gloss target="#t_ENDC1">ENDC</gloss>
                    </item>
                </list>
                <p>The Eighteen-Nation Disarmament Committee (<gloss target="#t_ENDC1">ENDC</gloss>)
                    is scheduled to resume its deliberations on March 6, 1969, in Geneva.</p>
                <p>In addition to the <gloss target="#t_NPT1">NPT</gloss> and the strategic arms
                    limitation talks, the agenda for the meeting includes the following complex arms
                    control issues on which the Administration does not now have a position: the
                    comprehensive test ban; cut-off of production of fissionable material for
                    nuclear weapons use; arms control on the seabed; and chemical and biological
                    warfare. There will be considerable pressure on the U.S. Delegation to establish
                    its current position on these and other important issues which have long been
                    included in the general U.S. position on arms control. The problem is
                    complicated by the fact that there appear to be major differences on all of
                    these issues within the U.S. Government.</p>
                <p>I believe that, prior to the resumption of the <gloss target="#t_ENDC1"
                        >ENDC</gloss>, these issues should be reviewed by the <gloss
                        target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> since they have such far-reaching security
                    implications.</p>
                <p>The staffing of these issues does not fit within any of the permanent groups
                    established so far under the <gloss target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss>. The Committee
                    of Principals, under the chairmanship of the Secretary of State, which
                    previously handled these matters has not been continued. I recommend, therefore,
                    that an ad hoc <gloss target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> group, under the chairmanship
                    of the Director of <gloss target="#t_ACDA1">ACDA</gloss> with representatives of
                    the appropriate agencies, be established to prepare a paper for the <gloss
                        target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss>’s consideration on an urgent basis. If you
                    approve, I have prepared the attached <gloss target="#t_NSSM1">NSSM</gloss>.</p>
                <p>Approve <gloss target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> meeting on the <gloss
                        target="#t_ENDC1">ENDC</gloss> [<persName corresp="#p_NRM1">Nixon</persName>
                    initialed] <lb/> Disapprove <lb/> Other</p>
                <p>Approve <gloss target="#t_NSSM1">NSSM</gloss> establishing ad hoc <gloss
                        target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> group [<persName corresp="#p_NRM1"
                        >Nixon</persName> initialed] <lb/> Disapprove <lb/> Other</p>
            </div>
